We need first to start from the opening book value of fixed assets (from the “Initial20231231001” record) and then adjust for any purchases (additions) and depreciation (reductions).

Step‑by‑step:

1. The “Initial20231231001” records give us three opening items. In particular, the Fixed Assets entry shows an initial book value of 5,000,000.00.

2. Look for any rows that “add” fixed assets. In our dataset these are marked by type “Fixed Assets Purchase”. We have two such rows:
 • One with an amount of 362,437.67 (for “Storage Facilities4”)
 • One with an amount of 303,640.51 (for “Processing Equipment5”)

– The total additions = 362,437.67 + 303,640.51 = 666,078.18

3. Look for any depreciation entries. We found two depreciation rows:
 • “Depreciation20240101001” with 45,748.20 
 • “Depreciation20240201002” with 54,491.69  
– Total depreciation = 45,748.20 + 54,491.69 = 100,239.89

4. So the net adjustment to the fixed assets value is:
 Final fixed assets = initial + additions – depreciation 
 = 5,000,000.00 + 666,078.18 – 100,239.89
 = 5,666,078.18 – 100,239.89 
 = 5,565,838.29

Thus, our solution is:

{
  "fixed assets net Initial Value": "5000000.00",
  "fixed assets net End Value": "5565838.29"
}
